The paper deals with computational geometry, specifically the problem of finding the shortest path for a snake amidst polygonal obstacles. This suggests that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also mentions that the problem is NP-hard, which implies that it involves complexity theory, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also discusses approximation algorithms, which suggests that cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) may be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions that the problem can be solved in polynomial time for a "fat" snake, which suggests that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) may also be a relevant sub-category.
